First of all it is not a good idea to implement database in blockchain.

But to solve your current problem you can make use of ABIEncoderV2 and wrap the inputs into struct.
There should not be more than 16 local stack variables in a solidity function, so your code is throwing error.

Here is the edited code:
```
pragma solidity &gt;=0.4.22 &lt;0.6.0;
pragma experimental ABIEncoderV2;
contract land{

    struct Landpaper{
        string holdname;
        uint number;
        string landaddress;
        string landnumber;
        string landpurpose;
        uint landgrades;
        uint256 landarea;
        string holdpoints;
        uint values;
        uint changefrequency;
    }

    mapping(uint256 =&gt; Landpaper) public id;

    function set(uint rfidnumber, Landpaper _landpaperRecord) public {
        id[rfidnumber]=_landpaperRecord;
    }
    
    function get(uint rfidnumber) view public returns(Landpaper){
        return id[rfidnumber];
    }

}
```
Find the documentation of ABIEncoder documentation [here][1] and web3 usage example [here][2].


  [1]: https://solidity.readthedocs.io/en/latest/abi-spec.html#handling-tuple-types
  [2]: https://blog.ricmoo.com/solidity-abiv2-a-foray-into-the-experimental-a6afd3d47185

